		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64320715"><p><div class="quote"><p>OK, so He-3 is perhaps a factor of 1000 more abundant on the moon than on the Earth. It's still way less than one part per million. Is the juice really worth the squeeze, or is this venture more accurately described as a way of mining naive investors?</p></div><p>One kilogram of He-3 is enough to produce around 9*10^7 kWh of energy. If we assume a very lousy 20% conversion efficiency, and a low wholesale prices of 5 cents per kWh, it's going to be around $10 million USD in gross profit. So a haul of 50 kilograms will be worth around $500 million.<br> <br>
That 50 kilograms will require processing around a million tons of regolith. So to be profitable, you probably need to keep it way below $500 per ton. This seems doable in theory, but practical challenges are going to be pretty steep.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64320715">
